The dataset covid_sequences.fa includes 200 sequences from the covid19 virus from different isolates across the world. A multiple sequence alignment of these sequences is found in the file covid_aligned_sequences.aln. These files are in “fast” format. Each sequence begins with header line that is prefixed a “>” character. The header includes a number of pieces of information about the sequence separated with “|” characters. e.g.

NC_045512 |Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2 isolate Wuhan-Hu-1| complete genome|China|Severe acute respiratory syndrome-related coronavirus|refseq| complete .

The header line is followed by the sequence which is spread across multiple lines until the next header line or the end of the file. Implement the following. Comment all code and submit alongside a brief writeup.

1. Implement code in python or R to compare the Jaccard distance between k-mers of any length from these sequences. *feel free to use any existing fasta parsers¶

In [5]:
#Using function created by Locken...
kmersSeq <- function(seq,k){
  kmers_seq <- c()
  for (i in 1:(length(seq)-k+1)){
    kmers_seq <- c(kmers_seq, as.character(substr(seq, i,i+k-1)))
  }
  return (kmers_seq)
}

jaccard_distance <- function(setA, setB, k) {
  seqa <- kmersSeq(setA, k)
  seqb <- kmersSeq(setB, k)
  AandB <- intersect(seqa, seqb)
  AorB <- union(seqa, seqb)
  return(1-length(AandB) / length(AorB))
}
t1<- Sys.time()  
jaccard_distance(covid_sequences[[2]], covid_sequences[[120]], 27)

     type="b", pch = 19, frame = FALSE, 
     xlab="Number of clusters K",
     ylab="Total within-clusters sum of squares")

#silhouette method
avg_silhouette_score <- function(k){
  km <- kmeans(NewhamDist, centers = k, nstart=40)
  ss <- silhouette(km$cluster, dist(NewhamDist, "euclidean"))
  mean(ss[, 3])
}
k <- 2:40 #minimum number of clusters for silhouette scores is 2 for between-cluster variation
avg_sil <- sapply(k, avg_silhouette_score)
k <- c(0, k)
avg_sil <- c(0, avg_sil)
plot(k, avg_sil, type='b', xlab='Number of clusters', ylab='Average Silhouette Scores', frame=FALSE, ylim = c(0,0.8))
According to the Elbow and Silhouette method, it is still hard to cluster those sequences. Suggesting the COVID19 has not formed stable clusters and are still evolving. 5. Write up a few sentences about what you infer from this tree and the evolution of the virus across the world.¶

From the tree using the UPGMA algorithm from hamming distances, we can roughly judge the similarity between sequences during the evolution of the COVID.

According to the Elbow and Silhouette method, it is still hard to cluster those sequences. Suggesting the COVID19 has not formed stable clusters and are still evolving.

When COVID first broke out, the rate of evolution was fast. The number of sequences in each cluster is small, and the sequences in the cluster see that the hammering distance is large; However, it's also possible that COVID 19 had started to evolve for some time before it was discovered. For example, the hamming distance between the sequence emb|LR757997 found in China in the early stage of the outbreak and the sequence emb|MT184908 found in the United States is very large. It may be because these two sequences were discovered in the early stage of the outbreak, when the evolvement rate is fast. But it is also can be the reason that COVID19 had started to evolve for some time before they were found, leading to great hamming distance.

With the further prevalence of COVID, clusters with a large number of sequences gradually appeared, and the hamming distance between sequences within the cluster was small, and even the hamming distance between several sequences can be zero. It indicated that the evolution rate slowed down and the COVID sequence gradually stabilized worldwide.Foe example, the sequence MT114418, LC542809, MT159706 were from different part of world, but there are extremely small hamming distances between them, showing the evolution slows down and becomes stable.

6.Bonus: How is the data presented on https://nextstrain.org an improvement on the results generated here?¶

  1. Its Phylogeny has more and more exhaustive data, including 2811 genomes sampled between Dec 2019 and May 2022.
  2. Its Phylogeny has a more detailed introduction to the time, variant, and collection country of each data collection.
  3. What interests me the most, and I have always wanted to implement it in my project, but what I did not achieve in the end is the interactivity of its Phylogeny, which can directly obtain relevant information by interacting with the web page.
  4. In addition, it also displays other icons, directly marking the density of COVID19 variants in various places on the world map, the current frequency of COVID19 variants, and so on.
